'''Golden Age of Russian Poetry''' is the name traditionally applied by philologists to the first half of the 19th century.<ref> {{cite web | url = http://www1.umn.edu/lol-russ/hpgary/Russ3421/lesson4.htm | title = LESSON 4 The Golden Age: Aleksandr Pushkin | accessdate = 2012-03-23 | last = John | first = Gary | date = 2009-08-07 | publisher = Department of Slavic and Central Asian Languages , University of Minnesota }}</ref> It is also called the Age of [[Pushkin]], after its most significant poet (in [[Vladimir Nabokov|Nabokov]]'s words, the greatest poet this world was blessed with since the time of [[Shakespeare]]<ref> {{cite book | last1 = Boyd | first1 = Brian | title = Stalking Nabokov: Selected Essays | publisher = Columbia University Press | year = 2011 | location = New York | pages = 203 | isbn = 0231158564 }}</ref>). [[Mikhail Lermontov]] and [[Fyodor Tyutchev]] are generally regarded as two most important Romantic poets after [[Pushkin]].<ref> {{cite book | last1 = Nabokov | first1 = Vladimir | title = Three Russian Poets: Selections from Pushkin, Lermontov, and Tyutchev | publisher = Norfolk: New Directions | year = 1944 | location = New York }}</ref> [[Vasily Zhukovsky]] and [[Konstantin Batyushkov]] are the best regarded of his precursors. Pushkin himself, however, considered [[Evgeny Baratynsky]] to be the finest poet of his day.<ref> {{cite web | url = http://russiapedia.rt.com/prominent-russians/literature/yevgeny-baratynsky/ | title = Prominent Russians: Yevgeny Baratynsky }}</ref>
