{{Mesopotamian myth (7)}}

The '''Hymn to Enlil''', '''Enlil and the Ekur (Enlil A)''', '''Hymn to the Ekur''', '''Hymn and incantation to Enlil''', '''Hymn to Enlil the all beneficent''' or '''Excerpt from an exorcism''' is a [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] [[myth]], written on [[clay tablet]]s in the late third millennium BC.<ref name="BorrásBarcelona2000">{{cite book|author1=Miguel Ángel Borrás|author2=Centre de Cultura Contemporània de Barcelona|title=Joan Goodrick Westenholz, The Foundation Myths of Mesopotamian Cities: Divine Planners and Human Builder in "La fundación de la ciudad: mitos y ritos en el mundo antiguo"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3yPVFGPr0aoC&pg=PA48|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=2000|publisher=Edicions UPC|isbn=978-84-8301-387-8|pages=48–}}</ref>

==Compilation==

Fragments of the text were discovered in the [[University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]] catalogue of the [[Akkadian language|Babylonian]] section (CBS) from their excavations at the [[temple]] [[library]] at [[Nippur]]. The [[myth]] was first published using tablet CBS 8317, translated by [[George Aaron Barton]] in 1918 as "Sumerian religious texts" in "[[Miscellaneous Babylonian Inscriptions]]", number ten, entitled "An excerpt from an [[exorcism]]".<ref name="Barton1918">{{cite book|author=George Aaron Barton|title=Miscellaneous Babylonian inscriptions, p. 60|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nn5hAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 May 2011|date=1918|publisher=Yale University Press}}</ref> The tablet is {{convert|3.4|by|2.75|by|1.2|in|cm}} at its thickest point. A larger fragment of the text was found on CBS tablet number 14152 and first published by Henry Frederick Lutz as "A hymn and incantation to Enlil" in "Selected Sumerian and Babylonian Texts", number 114 in 1919.<ref name="Lutz1919">{{cite book|author=Henry Frederick Lutz|title=Selected Sumerian and Babylonian texts, pp. 54-|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YX5DAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1919|publisher=The University Museum}}</ref> Barton's tablet had only containted lines five to twenty four of the reverse of Lutz's, which had already been translated in 1918 and was used to complete several of his damaged lines.<ref name="Barton1918"/>

[[Edward Chiera]] published tablet CBS 7924B from the hymn in "Sumerian Epics and Myths".<ref name="Chiera1964">{{cite book|author=Edward Chiera|title=Sumerian epics and myths, 102 B|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nEFCPgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|date=1964|publisher=The University of Chicago Press}}</ref> He also worked with [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] to publish three other tablets CBS 8473, 10226, 13869 in "Sumerian texts of varied contents" in 1934. The name given this time was "Hymn to the [[Ekur]]", suggesting the tablets were "parts of a composition which extols the ekur of Enlil at Nippur, it may, however be only an extract from a longer text".<ref name="ChieraKramer1934">{{cite book|author1=Edward Chiera|author2=Samuel Noah Kramer|author3=University of Pennsylvania. University Museum. Babylonian Section|title=Sumerian texts of varied contents, p. 4-|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHhiAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1934|publisher=The University of Chicago Press}}</ref> Further tablets were found to be part of the myth in the [[Hermann Volrath Hilprecht|Hilprecht]] collection at the [[University of Jena]], [[Germany]], numbers 1530, 1531, 1532, 1749b, 2610, 2648a and b, 2665, 2685, 1576 and 1577.<ref name="KramerBernhardt1961">{{cite book|author1=Samuel Noah Kramer|author2=Ines Bernhardt|title=Sumerische literarische Texte aus Nippur, pp. 19-20, 3 15, 3 16, 3 17, 3 18, 3 19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MTnWAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1961|publisher=Akademie-Verlag}}</ref> Further tablets containing the text were excavated at [[Isin]], modern Ishan al-Bahriyat, tablet 923.<ref name="etcsl">[http://www-etcsl.orient.ox.ac.uk/section4/b4051.htm ETCSL Enlil and the Ekur Bibliography]</ref> Another was found amongst the texts in the [[Iraq Museum]], tablet 44351a.<ref>Cuneiform texts of varying content. (Texts in the Iraq Museum 9, 13). Leiden: Brill, 1976.</ref> Others are held in the collections of the [[Abbey of Montserrat]] in [[Barcelona]] and the [[Ashmolean]] in [[Oxford]].<ref name="etcsl"/><ref name="MuseumLangdon1923">{{cite book|author1=Ashmolean Museum|title=Oxford editions of cuneiform inscriptions, Volume 11, 31|date=1923|publisher=Oxford university press, Clarendon}}</ref>

Other translations were made from tablets in the Nippur collection of the [[Istanbul Archaeology Museums|Museum of the Ancient Orient]] in [[Istanbul]] (Ni). [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] amongst others worked to translate several others from the Istanbul collection including Ni 1039, 1180, 4005, 4044, 4150, 4339, 4377, 4584, 9563 and 9698.<ref name="Kramer1944">{{cite book|author=Samuel Noah Kramer|title=Sumerian literary texts from Nippur: in the Museum of the Ancient Orient at Istanbul, 37 & 56|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hqdIGQAACAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|date=1944|publisher=American Schools of Oriental Research}}</ref><ref name="CigKizilyay1969">{{cite book|author1=Muazzez Cig|author2=Hatice Kizilyay|title=Sumerian literary tablets and fragments in the archeological museum of Istanbul-I, 68, 1f, 94 & 114|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vrEnGwAACAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|date=1969|publisher=Tarih Kurumu Basimevi}}</ref> More were found at [[Henri de Genouillac]]'s excavations at [[Kish (Sumer)|Kish]] (C 53).<ref name="Genouillac1924">{{cite book|author=[[Henri de Genouillac]]|title=Premières recherches archéologiques à Kich: Mission d'Henri de Genouillac 1911 - 1912. Rapport sur les travaux et inventaires, fac-similés, dessins, photographies et plans, C 53|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RoAptwAACAAJ|accessdate=2 June 2011|date=1924|publisher=Édouard Champion}}</ref> Another tablet of the myth (Si 231) was excavated at [[Sippar]] in the collections of the [[Istanbul]] Archaeological Museum.<ref name="Falkenstein">Falkenstein, Adam., Sumerische Götterlieder (Volume 1 of 2): Abhandlungen der Heidelberg Akademie der Wissenschaften - philosophisch-historische Klasse  Jahrgang 1959, 1, 1, pl. 1f, 2f and 4, Abhandlung, Carl Winter Universitätsverlag, 1959.</ref> Sir [[Charles Leonard Woolley]] unearthed more tablets at [[Ur]] contained in the "Ur excavations texts" from 1928.<ref name="Mesopotamiamuseum1928">{{cite book|author1=British museum and Pennsylvania University. University museum. Joint expedition to Mesopotamia|author2=Pennsylvania University. University museum|title=Ur excavations texts... 6 65, 6 371, 6 *14 and 6 *63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4GF1QwAACAAJ|accessdate=28 May 2011|date=1928|publisher=British museum}}</ref> Other tablets and versions were used to bring the myth to its present form with the latest translations presented by [[Thorkild Jacobsen]], Miguel Civil and Joachim Krecher.<ref name="etcsl"/><ref name="Falkenstein"/><ref name="Jacobsen1997">{{cite book|author=Thorkild Jacobsen|title=The Harps that once--: Sumerian poetry in translation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L-BI0h41yCEC|accessdate=4 June 2011|date=23 September 1997|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-07278-5}}</ref>

==Composition==

The hymn, noted by Kramer as one of the most important of its type,<ref name="Kramer1964">{{cite book|author=Samuel Noah Kramer|title=The Sumerians: their history, culture and character|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iY9xp4pLp88C&pg=PA205|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1964|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-45238-8|pages=205–}}</ref> starts with praise for Enlil in his awe-inspiring dais:

{{cquote|Enlil's commands are by far the loftiest, his words are holy, his utterances are immutable! The fate he decides is everlasting, his glance makes the mountains anxious, his ... reaches into the interior of the mountains. All the gods of the earth bow down to father Enlil, who sits comfortably on the holy dais, the lofty engur, to Nunamnir, whose lordship and princeship are most perfect. The [[Annanuki]] enter before him and obey his instructions faithfully.<ref name="etcsl"/>}}

The hymn develops by relating Enlil founding and creating the origin of the city of Nippur and his organization of the earth.<ref name="Kramer1972">{{cite book|author=Samuel Noah Kramer|title=Sumerian mythology: a study of spiritual and literary achievement in the third millennium B.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ga6jAe9hSaAC&pg=PR15|accessdate=4 June 2011|date=1972|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-1047-7|pages=15–}}</ref> In contrast to the myth of [[Enlil and Ninlil]] where the city exists before creation, here Enlil is shown to be responsible for its planning and construction, suggesting he surveyed and drew the plans before its creation:

{{cquote|When you mapped out the holy settlement on the earth, You built the city Nippur by yourself, Enlil. The Kiur, your pure place. In the Duranki, in the middle of the four quarters of the earth, you founded it. Its soil is the life of the land ([[Sumer]])<ref name="BorrásBarcelona2000"/>}}

The hymn moves on from the physical construction of the city and gives a description and veneration of its [[ethics]] and moral code:

{{cquote|The powerful lord, who is exceedingly great in heaven and earth, who knows judgement, who is wise. He of great wisdom takes his seat in the [[Duranki]]. In princeship he makes the [[Kiur]], the great place, come forth radiantly. In Nippur, the 'bond' of heaven and earth, he establishes his place of residence. The City - its panorama is a terrifying radiance. To him who speaks mightily it does not grant life. It permits no inimical word to be spoken in judgement, no improper speech, hostile words, hostility, and unseemingliness, no evil, oppression, looking askance, acting without regard, slandering, arrogance, the breaking of promises. These abominations the city does not permit. The evil and wicked man do not escape its hand. The city, which is bestowed with steadfastness. For which righteousness and justice have been made a lasting possession.<ref name="BorrásBarcelona2000"/>}}

The last sentence has been compared by R. P. Gordon to the description of [[Jerusalem]] in the [[Book of Isaiah]] ({{Bibleverse||Isaiah|1:21|HE}}), "the city of justice, righteousness dwelled in her" and in the [[Book of Jeremiah]] ({{Bibleverse||Jeremiah|31:23|HE}}), "O habitation of justice, and mountain of holiness."<ref name="Gordon1995">{{cite book|author=R. P. Gordon|title="The place is too small for us": the Israelite prophets in recent scholarship|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mf3ZeuTyXiUC&pg=PA48|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1995|publisher=Eisenbrauns|isbn=978-1-57506-000-2|pages=48–}}</ref> The myth continues with the city's inhabitants building a temple dedicated to Enlil, referred to as the [[Ekur]]. The priestly positions and responsibilities of the Ekur are listed along with an appeal for Enlil's blessings on the city, where he is regarded as the source of all prosperity:

{{cquote|Without the Great Mountain, Enlil, no city would be built, no settlement would be founded; no cow-pen would be built, no sheepfold would be established; no king would be elevated, no lord would be given birth; no high priest or priestess would perform [[extispicy]]; soldiers would have no generals or captains; no carp-filled waters would ... the rivers at their peak; the carp would not ... come straight up from the sea, they would not dart about. The sea would not produce all its heavy treasure, no freshwater fish would lay eggs in the reedbeds, no bird of the sky would build nests in the spacious land; in the sky the thick clouds would not open their mouths; on the fields, dappled grain would not fill the arable lands, vegetation would not grow lushly on the plain; in the gardens, the spreading forests of the mountain would not yield fruits. Without the Great Mountain, Enlil, Nintud would not kill, she would not strike dead; no cow would drop its calf in the cattle-pen, no ewe would bring forth ... lamb in its sheepfold; the living creatures which multiply by themselves would not lie down in their ... ; the four-legged animals would not propagate, they would not mate.<ref name="etcsl"/>}}

A similar passage to the last lines above has been noted in the Biblical Psalms ({{Bibleverse||Psalms|29:9|HE}}) "The voice of the Lord makes hinds to calve and makes goats to give birth (too) quickly".<ref name="StolWiggermann2000">{{cite book|author1=Marten Stol|author2=F. A. M. Wiggermann|title=Birth in Babylonia and the Bible: its Mediterranean setting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-n4LQNeU1ckC&pg=PA27|accessdate=4 June 2011|date=2000|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-72371-89-8|pages=27–}}</ref> The hymn concludes with further reference to Enlil as a farmer and praise for his wife, [[Ninlil]]:

{{cquote|When it relates to the earth, it brings prosperity: the earth will produce prosperity. Your word means flax, your word means grain. Your word means the early flooding, the life of the lands. It makes the living creatures, the animals (?) which copulate and breathe joyfully in the greenery. You, Enlil, the good shepherd, know their ways ... the sparkling stars. You married Ninlil, the holy consort, whose words are of the heart, her of noble countenance in a holy ma garment, her of beautiful shape and limbs, the trustworthy lady of your choice. Covered with allure, the lady who knows what is fitting for the E-kur, whose words of advice are perfect, whose words bring comfort like fine oil for the heart, who shares the holy throne, the pure throne with you, she takes counsel and discusses matters with you. You decide the fates together at the place facing the sunrise. Ninlil, the lady of heaven and earth, the lady of all the lands, is honoured in the praise of the Great Mountain.<ref name="etcsl"/>}}

[[Andrew R. George]] suggested that the hymn to Enlil "can be incorporated into longer compositions" as with the [[Kesh temple hymn]] and "the hymn to temples in Ur that introduces a [[Self-praise of Shulgi (Shulgi D)|Shulgi hymn]]."<ref name="George1992">{{cite book|author=A. R. George|title=Babylonian topographical texts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zw0TQ1MrhOkC&pg=PA3|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1992|publisher=Peeters Publishers|isbn=978-90-6831-410-6|pages=3–}}</ref>

==Discussion==

The poetic form and laudatory content of the hymn have shown similarities to the [[Book of Psalms]] in the [[Bible]], particularly Psalm 23 ({{Bibleverse||Psalms|23:1-2|HE}}) "The Lord is my shepherd, I shall not want, he maketh me to lie down in green pastures."<ref name="Bullock2007">{{cite book|author=C. Hassell Bullock|title=An Introduction to the Old Testament Poetic Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QSGZbt7isfQC&pg=PA45|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1 September 2007|publisher=Moody Publishers|isbn=978-0-8024-4157-7|pages=45–}}</ref> Line eighty four mentions:

{{cquote|Enlil, if you look upon the shepherd favourably, if you elevate the one truly called in the Land, then the foreign countries are in his hands, the foreign countries are at his feet! Even the most distant foreign countries submit to him.<ref name="etcsl"/>}}

and in line ninety one, Enlil is referred to as a shepherd:

{{cquote|Enlil, faithful shepherd of the teeming multitudes, herdsman, leader of all living creatures.<ref name="etcsl"/>}}

The shepherd motif originating in this myth is also found describing [[Jesus]] in the [[Book of John]] ({{Bibleverse||John|10:11-13|KJV}}).<ref name="BeutlerFortna2005">{{cite book|author1=Johannes Beutler|author2=Robert T. Fortna|title=The Shepherd Discourse of John 10 and Its Context|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07PzorWos1wC&pg=PA38|accessdate=4 June 2011|date=15 December 2005|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-02060-2|pages=38–}}</ref> [[Joan Goodnick Westenholz|Joan Westenholz]] noted that "The farmer image was even more popular than the shepherd in the earliest personal names, as might be expected in an agrarian society." She notes that both Falkenstein and Thorkild Jacobsen consider the farmer refers to the king of Nippur; Reisman has suggested that the farmer or 'engar' of the Ekur was likely to be [[Ninurta]].<ref name="PanainoPiras2004">{{cite book|author1=Antonio Panaino|author2=Andrea Piras|title=Schools of oriental studies and the development of modern historiography: proceedings of the Fourth annual symposium of the Assyrian and Babylonian intellectual heritage project held in Ravenna, Italy, October 13-17, 2001|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kR_vjs-1AQEC&pg=PA285|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=2004|publisher=Mimesis Edizioni|isbn=978-88-8483-206-1|pages=285–}}</ref> The term appears in line sixty

{{cquote|Its great farmer is the good shepherd of the Land, who was born vigorous on a propitious day. The farmer, suited for the broad fields, comes with rich offerings; he does not ...... into the shining E-kur.<ref name="etcsl"/>}}

Wayne Horowitz discusses the use of the word [[abzu]], normally used as a name for an abzu temple, god, cosmic place or cultic water basin. In the hymn to Enlil, its interior is described as a 'distant sea':

{{cquote|Its (Ekur's) [[me (mythology)|me]]'s (ordinances) are ''me''s of the [[Abzu]] which no-one can understand. Its interior is a distant sea which 'Heaven's Edge' cannot comprehend.<ref name="Horowitz1998">{{cite book|author=Wayne Horowitz|title=Mesopotamian cosmic geography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P8fl8BXpR0MC&pg=PA308|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=1998|publisher=Eisenbrauns|isbn=978-0-931464-99-7|pages=308–}}</ref>}}

The foundations of Enlil's temple are made of [[lapis lazuli]], which has been linked to the ''"soham"'' stone used in the [[Book of Ezekiel]] ({{Bibleverse||Ezekiel|28:13|HE}}) describing the materials used in the building of ''"[[Garden of Eden|Eden]], the [[Garden of the gods (Sumerian paradise)|Garden of god]]"'' perched on ''"the mountain of the lord"'', [[Zion]], and in the [[Book of Job]] ({{Bibleverse||Job|28:6-16|HE}}) ''"The stones of it are the place of sapphires and it hath dust of gold"''.<ref name="Hess1999"/> [[Moses]] also saw God's feet standing on a ''"paved work of a sapphire stone"'' in ({{Bibleverse||Exodus|24:10|HE}}). Precious stones are also later repeated in a similar context describing decoration of the walls of [[New Jerusalem]] in the [[Apocalypse]] ({{Bibleverse||Revelation|21:21|KJV}}).<ref name="GarryEl-Shamy2005">{{cite book|author1=Jane Garry|author2=Hasan M. El-Shamy|title=Archetypes and motifs in folklore and literature: a handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cn6pWMverBIC&pg=PA198|accessdate=14 June 2011|date=2005|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-1260-1|pages=198–}}</ref>

{{cquote|You founded it in the [[Dur-an-ki]], in the middle of the four quarters of the earth. Its soil is the life of the Land, and the life of all the foreign countries. Its brickwork is red gold, its foundation is [[lapis lazuli]]. You made it glisten on high.<ref name="Hess1999">{{cite book|author=Richard S. Hess|title=Zion, city of our God|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lk_xLfQ_SRAC&pg=PA100|accessdate=14 June 2011|date=June 1999|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|isbn=978-0-8028-4426-2|pages=100–}}</ref>}}

Along with the [[Kesh Temple Hymn]], Steve Tinney has identified the Hymn to Enlil as part of a standard sequence of [[scribe|scribal]] training scripts he refers to as the [[Decad (Sumerian texts)|Decad]]. He suggested that "the Decad constituted a required program of literary learning, used almost without exception throughout Babylonia. The Decad thus included almost all literary types available in Sumerian."<ref name="Veldhuis2004">{{cite book|author=Niek Veldhuis|title=Religion, literature, and scholarship: the Sumerian composition Nanše and the birds, with a catalogue of Sumerian bird names|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4kPs3vicwI4C&pg=PA63|accessdate=3 June 2011|date=2004|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-13950-3|pages=63–}}</ref><ref>Tinney, Steve., On the Curricular Setting of Sumerian Literature, Iraq 61: 159-172. Forthcoming Elementary Sumerian  Literary Texts. MC.</ref>

